  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback (RLHF) has become a dominant paradigm to further align LLMs with human preferences after pretraining and supervised fine-tuning.",
    "The seminal work from Ouyang et al. (2022) popularized RLHF for LLMs by introducing a three-step process: (a) collecting human preference data comparing model outputs, (b) training a reward model to predict these preferences, and (c) fine-tuning the LLM using reinforcement learning to optimize for the learned reward signal.",
    "However, RLHF relies on large amounts of preference data and a learned reward function that is imperfect and opaque, which can lead to issues like reward hacking (Liu et al., 2024; Bai et al., 2022a).",
    "To mitigate these issues, recent work has explored alternative reward signals that are more transparent and verifiable.",
    "For instance, in domains with clear correctness criteria, such as coding and math, researchers have leveraged programmatic success signals (e.g., passing unit tests or reaching a known answer) to train models via reinforcement learning and significantly improve LLMs' reasoning capabilities (Guo et al., 2025; Yu et al., 2025; Luo et al., 2025; Gao et al., 2025; Lin et al., 2025)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For instance, in domains with clear correctness criteria, such as coding and math, researchers have leveraged programmatic success signals (e.g., passing unit tests or reaching a known answer) to train models via reinforcement learning and significantly improve LLMs' reasoning capabilities (Guo et al., 2025; Yu et al., 2025; Luo et al., 2025; Gao et al., 2025; Lin et al., 2025)."
  ]
